<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0826-B"><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>In the Senate, Abramoff befriended Republicans and their staffers, along with some Democrats on the appropriations committees.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="12,37,6"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051123.0159"><line>Investigators are looking at half a dozen members of Congress, current and former senior Capitol Hill aides, a former deputy secretary of the interior, and Abramoff's former lobbying colleagues, according to sources familiar with the probe who spoke on the condition of anonymity.<annotation scu-count="7" sum-count="3" sums="37,55,6"><scu uid="17" label="Investigators investigating aides " weight="1"/><scu uid="17" label="Investigators investigating aides " weight="1"/><scu uid="16" label="Investigators investigating congressmen" weight="1"/><scu uid="18" label="Investigators investigating government officials" weight="1"/><scu uid="18" label="Investigators investigating government officials" weight="1"/><scu uid="19" label="Investigators investigating lobbyists" weight="1"/><scu uid="19" label="Investigators investigating lobbyists" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>Further, Dickstein said he knows of no involvement by Reed, the Christian Coalition or any other Abramoff-connected groups lobbying against the United Auburn decision.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>&quot;If anyone is not surprised at the rise and fall of Jack Abramoff, it is me,&quot; said Rich Bond, a former chairman of the Republican National Committee.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>In October, Abramoff sent a letter to state College Republican chairs urging them to raise money through direct mail.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>&quot;I think it is bigger than any congressional scandal I can remember and certainly politically it touches hundreds of members,&quot; said Kenneth Gross, a former Federal Election Commission attorney.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Bhutto's Washington lobbyists were at the Pakistani embassy savoring her successful meeting with President Bill Clinton when a man in a suit made a mysterious entrance.</line><line>Abramoff declined to comment for this article.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line><line>The movie ran into financial difficulty during and after production, but Abramoff produced a sequel, &quot;Red Scorpion 2.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>President Bush is giving $6,000 to the American Heart Association.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>Howard Dean, chairman of the Democratic National Committee, seized on Abramoff's court appearance to call on the president to return the more than $100,000 that Abramoff raised for Bush's campaign.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>The person spoke on condition of anonymity because the probe is ongoing.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Lawmakers and their aides packed his restaurants and skyboxes and jetted off with him on golf trips to Scotland and the Pacific island of Saipan.</line><line>Soon they made headlines with such tactics as demolishing a mock Berlin Wall in Lafayette Park, where they also burned a Soviet leader in effigy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>But nothing in the e-mails and other documents uncovered by the Senate Indian Affairs Committee's probe of the scandal proves Doolittle and Abramoff were working together on the tribal cases.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Bloomingdale died in 1982.</line><line>Due to our efforts and other circumstances, Kennedy will not plague us in 1984.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;I didn't know on whose behalf he had interceded precisely and on whose behalf Mr. Griles was exercising that inquiry.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Former lobbyist Jack Abramoff's second guilty plea in two days sealed his role as a star witness in the federal government's largest congressional corruption investigation in decades.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="8" sums="14,29,32,37,41,51,55,6"><scu uid="7" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty" weight="1"/><scu uid="7" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He pushed his own associates for government positions, from which they, too, could help him.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>This activity cannot be funded through College Republicans, nor will the RNC permit the use of its facilities for these purposes.&quot;</line><line>Abramoff was admonished by RNC official Bond after a letter to the Palestine Liberation Organization went out over RNC stationery, according to a memo.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line><line>WASHINGTON - In 1981, a newly elected president was about to shift the nation rightward, and a 22-year-old Brandeis graduate named Jack Abramoff - savoring his own victory as the newly elected chairman of the College Republicans - was hatching plans to transform the nation's young people into stalwart Reaganites.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="0,9"/></line><line>But, Bond said, &quot;speculative direct mail&quot; by the College Republicans was &quot;completely unauthorized.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Abramoff's sentence in the Florida case is to be served concurrently with the penalty in the Washington case.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Determined to find financial footing independent of the RNC, Abramoff proposed setting up a separate group, the College Republican National Fund, whose income would be tax-exempt.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>Abramoff's appearance in a federal courtroom to acknowledge his wrongdoing not only punctuated a spectacular political fall but sent a shiver across Capitol Hill, where much of the federal corruption investigation is focused in an election year that will determine control of Congress in the final year of the Bush presidency.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="29"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>&quot;I'm going to talk at length about the need for us to rethink not just lobbying but the whole process of elections, incumbency protection and the way in which the system has evolved,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Abramoff's top lieutenants were two figures who would achieve their own prominence: Grover Norquist, the Harvard MBA who would become Washington's leading antitax activist, and Ralph Reed, who would build the Christian Coalition into a powerful GOP player in the 1990s.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Even in those early days, there were hints of the troubles to come.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>&quot;People are uneasy about what else is out there,&quot; said one GOP strategist who requested anonymity to speak more candidly about the possible political fallout.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051123.0159"><line>His help is expected to be crucial to the Justice Department's wide-ranging Abramoff investigation, which began early last year after the revelation that Scanlon and the lobbyist took in tens of millions of dollars from Indian tribes unaware of their secret partnership to jack up fees and split profits.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="10,38"><scu uid="30" label="Abramoff to provide testimony in corruption probe of executive branch agencies" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>end adv26</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>The political ramifications of the Abramoff probe were apparent, with minority Democrats intending to make ethics a campaign issue in this election year.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>A year later, Abramoff left the College Republicans to pursue other ventures.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>Abramoff's activities went &quot;far beyond lawful lobbying to the illegal practice of paying for official acts,&quot; Fisher said at her news conference.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>This is by no means a slam dunk for the government, even with Abramoff part of the prosecution team now.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Bond, now a former RNC official, characterized Abramoff's assertion that he had gained access to the RNC contributor list as &quot;outside the realm of reality.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Shortly thereafter, Abramoff was running Citizens for America, a conservative grass-roots group founded by drug-store magnate Lewis E. Lehrman.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>A Burns aide said the senator has not been implicated in any of the Abramoff investigations, and has not hired a lawyer to handle the case.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>He borrowed money for his cause, even from his father.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>However, the plea agreement detailed lavish gifts, travel and contributions that match those Abramoff gave to House Administration Committee Chairman Bob Ney, R-Ohio.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051123.0159"><line>A onetime congressional staffer who became a top partner to lobbyist Jack Abramoff pleaded guilty to conspiring to bribe a congressman and other public officials and agreed to pay back more than $19 million he fraudulently charged Indian tribal clients.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="4" sums="16,21,23,29"><scu uid="34" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to conspiracy" weight="3"/><scu uid="7" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>Scott Shepard's e-mail address is sshepard@coxnews.com.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>&quot;The contributions given to my political committees by Jack Abramoff and his clients, while legal and fully disclosed, have served to undermine the public's confidence in its government,&quot; Burns said in a statement explaining his reversal.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>The memo was sent to the committee chairman, Richard Richards, after a ride in Richards's limousine back from the White House.</line><line>&quot;We were sick to death of being on the RNC leash.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Kidan and another Abramoff partner, Michael Scanlon, already have pleaded guilty and agreed to cooperate with the investigation.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="25" label="Scanlon's help is crucial to Abramoff investigation" weight="2"/><scu uid="25" label="Scanlon's help is crucial to Abramoff investigation" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>They forged political ties, but the two men never became personally close, according to associates of both men.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Alfred Bloomingdale, a close personal friend of my family, told me to contact you immediately,&quot; Abramoff wrote to Roy Cohn, Joseph McCarthy's one-time counsel, on July 8, 1981.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Ney, who received favors and contributions from Abramoff, placed comments in the Congressional Record that pressured SunCruz's owner, Konstantinos &quot;Gus&quot; Boulis, to sell his fleet to Abramoff and Kidan.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He was a man of contradictions.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>The court said it was not enough that the cooperative had two regulatory issues before the department.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>At a minimum, Tuesday's developments put both sides of the lawmaker-lobbyist relationship on notice that some of the wilder customs of recent years -- lubricated with money, entertainment and access -- carry higher risks.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>Abramoff, the papers state, paid the staffer's wife $50,000 (euro41,400) from clients that benefited from the actions of the staffer, identified by a person close to the investigation as Tony Rudy, DeLay's former deputy chief of staff.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="2" sums="40,5"><scu uid="22" label="Investigators investigating Tony Rudy" weight="1"/><scu uid="22" label="Investigators investigating Tony Rudy" weight="1"/><scu uid="22" label="Investigators investigating Tony Rudy" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Abramoff added that &quot;because of his close association with the President, Mr. Bloomingdale was able to free up the RNC contributor list for our use.</line><line>More than two decades later, in early January, Abramoff became a symbol of Washington corruption when he pleaded guilty to a range of crimes committed as a lobbyist.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>The latest to do so was House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who disclosed late Tuesday afternoon that he would donate some $70,000 in Abramoff-related donations to charities.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Abramoff's election as chairman - after a campaign that cost him $10,000 - changed all that.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>When the film was released in 1989, anti-apartheid groups demonstrated at the theaters.</line><line>A friend of two decades, Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., defended Abramoff: &quot;I think he's been dealt a bad hand and the worst, rawest deal I've ever seen in my life.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>&quot;Words will not ever be able to express my sorrow and my profound regret for all my actions and mistakes,&quot; an uncharacteristically contrite Abramoff admitted to Huvelle after pleading guilty to federal charges of conspiracy, fraud and tax evasion.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>But some who spoke on the condition of anonymity said they look back in amazement at the heady days of Abramoff's rise.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>The Abramoff case &quot;is clearly a much bigger scandal than the House bank or a book,&quot; Fenn said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>They signed on for the camaraderie, the paycheck, the excitement.</line><line>Those within Abramoff's circle also saw the danger signs.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;But what he did was ineffectual.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>The Florida and Washington cases were resolved together in an agreement that requires the ex-lobbyist to provide evidence and testimony in the Justice Department's probe of corruption in Congress and executive branch agencies.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>In a recent interview, Stillwell said he accepted dinners at Abramoff's restaurant, Signatures, and tickets to Redskins games.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>At the close of the Student Liberation Day celebration, Abramoff, Erickson, and others traveled to the White House to attend a reception for the American medical students who had been rescued in the invasion.</line><line>&quot;I remember them being in debt and constantly having financial issues,&quot; said William I. Greener III, a former RNC communications director.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>The following year, Abramoff figured out how to use his clients to fund his own trips to St. Andrews with lawmakers.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>&quot;At the time I dealt with Jack Abramoff, I obviously did not know, and had no way of knowing, the self-serving and fraudulent nature of Abramoff's activities,&quot; the statement said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="13,36,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Jack governed by sheer force of will,&quot; Erickson said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>Some analysts have suggested it could rival the House banking scandal that presaged the GOP takeover of Congress a dozen years ago.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>A training manual from the period, which Reed helped to write, described Ralph Nader's network of Public Interest Research Groups on campus as &quot;tyrannical&quot; and &quot;radical.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;The congressman has never talked to Ralph Reed regarding Indian gaming issues, and we are unaware of what Ms. Federici is specifically referring to in her memo other than the congressman's long-held opposition to the expansion of gaming in this country,&quot; Blackann said.</line><line>Doolittle's office essentially agreed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Bond and Kaufman also recalled asking Abramoff to move out.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>Abramoff was watching the United Auburn case closely because the Interior Department ruling on it could become a damaging precedent for his clients, the Louisiana Coushattas, who were trying to torpedo a Louisiana casino proposed by the Jena Band of Choctaws.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Jack was a difficult person to work with from a lawyer's point of view,&quot; Braden said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>Campaign finance experts say the donations are perfectly legal, so long as the original contribution did not violate the law.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;He seems to be distinguishing how Norton would handle Jena (I hope),&quot; Rudy wrote, then added that Abramoff's team was going to have to be &quot;mega careful&quot; on how they lobby the department.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>&quot;In this case, you do.</line><line>&quot;He defrauded the tribes, he defrauded his law firms, so why isn't it that he defrauded public officials as well?&quot; said Jan W. Baran, an attorney at Wiley Rein &amp; Fielding.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>&quot;I wouldn't be surprised to see lawmakers become cautious in meetings with lobbyists.&quot;</line><line>Some lobbyists reacted defensively Tuesday, at pains to say that Abramoff was an exception to the way they do business.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>By the summer of 2001, Abramoff was referring to him in an e-mail to a client as &quot;our guy Steve Griles.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>Court papers in Abramoff's case refer to an aide to then-House Majority Leader Tom DeLay who helped stop anti-gambling legislation regarding the Internet.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>&quot;The Justice Department will aggressively investigate and prosecute these types of cases which have a devastating impact on the public's trust of government.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>The biggest public corruption scandal in a generation Tuesday took down one of the best-connected lobbyists in Washington.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="44"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He produced two Hollywood movies.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Regardless of the electoral implications, the Abramoff scandal may force changes on Capitol Hill in the form of tough new lobbying disclosure laws that even some lobbying advocates say it is time to consider.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>The court papers in the Washington case refer to Ney, saying that regarding SunCruz, the congressman placed a statement drafted by Abramoff partner Michael Scanlon in the Congressional Record.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>&quot;If people get disgusted by the relationship between the people in power and the lobbyists, [Abramoff] is going to become their poster boy.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>But he said that all those actions occurred while he was a contract employee at Interior, not a federal worker.</line><line>They had never heard of him.</line><line>When Republicans wrested control of the House from the Democrats in 1994, Abramoff turned his focus back to Washington politics.</line><line>Team Abramoff</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Under Abramoff, the College Republicans office quickly became a nesting ground for hard-right believers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Sens.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Look how the seeds of his current destruction are so evident,&quot; said Richard Bond, who as RNC deputy chairman repeatedly confronted Abramoff over spending issues.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>Doolittle's office, moreover, denied the congressman coordinated efforts with Abramoff on the United Auburn casino, which ultimately opened in 2003.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="20" label="Investigators investigating Doolittle" weight="1"/><scu uid="20" label="Investigators investigating Doolittle" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>While Democrats seek to taint Burns with the Abramoff scandal, the National Republican Senatorial Committee has gone on the offense, pointing out that Abramoff gave cash not only to Baucus, but to Harry Reid of Nevada, Senate minority leader and the Democrats' leader.</line><line>Democrats believe the ensuing voter anger contributed to their loss of dozens of seats in 2004, giving control of the chamber to Republicans.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>In the post-Abramoff era, what once was accepted as business as usual may be seen as questionable or worse.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>House Speaker Dennis Hastert became the most recent addition to the roster of politicians announcing plans to donate Abramoff's campaign contributions to charity.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>But we were really worried about the group and the direction they were taking.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>&quot;Part of it is to get rid of money that for them is hot.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>With Savimbi, Abramoff organized a &quot;convention&quot; of anticommunist guerrillas from Laos, Nicaragua and Afghanistan in a remote part of Angola.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>Some tribes like the Saginaw Chippewa and the Mississippi band of Choctaw Indians are getting campaign contributions back.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Dissent within the ranks</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>The initial impact of a scandal that earlier produced a guilty plea from Abramoff associate Michael Scanlon could be changes in the way lawmakers and lobbyists interact.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>On College Republican stationery, Abramoff wrote: &quot;While the Student Liberation Day Coalition is nonpartisan and intended only for educational purposes, I don't need to tell you how important this project is to our efforts as CRs.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>In a statement released Tuesday after Abramoff's plea, Ney denied any wrongdoing in his dealings with Abramoff.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="22"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>In the longer term, said many lobbyists and others, Congress will be pressured to revisit and toughen rules on gifts and travel that lawmakers and their staffs may accept.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He opened two restaurants close to the Capitol.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>I don't think so.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>He faces up to 11 years in prison.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Abramoff also worked on behalf of the apartheid South African government, which secretly paid $1.5 million a year to the International Freedom Foundation, a nonprofit group that Abramoff operated out of a townhouse in the 1980s, according to sworn testimony to the South African Truth and Reconciliation Commission.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>&quot;And if he broke laws, he needs to be held to account and he needs to be punished.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>In a favorite bit, he would mimic an ice-cold Michael Corleone facing down a crooked politician's demand for a cut of Mafia gambling profits: &quot;Senator, you can have my answer now if you like.</line><line>A reconstruction of the lobbyist's rise and fall shows that he was an ingenious dealmaker who hatched interlocking schemes that exploited the machinery of government and trampled the norms of doing business in Washington -- sometimes for clients but more often to serve his desire for wealth and influence.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;We had heard rumors that (White House political strategist) Karl Rove had been called, that Doolittle had set up a meeting with Griles -- and these e-mails confirm that in my mind for the first time,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>In 1984, the foundation helped organize &quot;Student Liberation Day&quot; in support of Reagan's invasion of Grenada.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Abramoff Wednesday admitted in U.S. District Court in Miami that he engaged in fraud and conspiracy in his purchase of a fleet of casino boats in 2000, when he presented lenders with a counterfeit document showing that he and a partner had put $23 million into the deal.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>It was unclear how much exactly the campaign would be giving to charity since McClellan referred questions about the matter to the Republican National Committee, which did not immediately return phone calls about it.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Yet Abramoff also transformed the once-sleepy College Republican campus clubs into a vibrant political force, enjoying access to members of Congress, especially Newt Gingrich, the little-known backbencher who would later become House speaker.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>On Wednesday, Abramoff was to plead guilty in Miami to criminal charges stemming from Abramoff's 2000 purchase of SunCruz Casinos, a case that touches on Rep. Bob Ney, a Republican.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Montana Senators Max Baucus, a Democrat, and Conrad Burns, a Republican, were the latest to return Abramoff-connected cash.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>&quot;Right now, the center is a lobbying and PAC (political action committee) system center, which is not healthy.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>As one solicitation suggests, the fund had clear political intent.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>&quot;Suddenly, this portly guy steps in and sits down.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;If I had known the CRs were out getting loans from people that they potentially couldn't pay back, I would have stopped them dead in their tracks,&quot; said Bond.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>And Fisher declined reporters' requests for the names as well.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>&quot;There needs to be greater transparency and better enforcement.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;It looks like Doolittle is not giving up and that the conservatives a(re) being mobilized,&quot; Federici wrote.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Former House speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who with Weber's help effectively used issues of corruption to wrest control of the House from Democrats in 1994, said the Abramoff scandal should trigger a broader review in Congress of the way politicians finance campaigns and deal with lobbyists.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>I have no doubt that we will pyramid that $50,000, to over $1 million within the first year.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>The White Buffalo Woman Calf Society, a center for battered women in tiny Mission, S.D., is far removed from the Jack Abramoff lobbying scandal that rocked Washington this week.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="44"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>He and Norquist brought to Washington the same energy they had applied to organizing Massachusetts campuses for Reagan.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;I am really worried about this,&quot; Abramoff wrote.</line><line>&quot;We would rather that he had done nothing, obviously,&quot; Howard Dickstein, the Auburn tribe's attorney, said of Doolittle.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Words like bribery are being used to describe things that happened every day in Washington and are not bribes.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>&quot;The wrongdoing that he apparently now is acknowledging he was involved in is outrageous,&quot; McClellan said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Abramoff's defenders say he was trying to build a far more potent political force than other affiliates, with a national program to train conservative activists.</line><line>By then, the College Republicans had been banished not only from the RNC premises but also from the Reagan White House.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Abramoff's lobbying team was made up of Republicans and a few Democrats, most of whom he had wined and dined when they were aides to powerful members of Congress.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>E-mails uncovered by a Senate committee show superlobbyist Jack Abramoff had a keen interest in Rep. John Doolittle's unsuccessful effort to block approval of the United Auburn Indian Community's Thunder Valley casino in Placer County, Calif.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="14,42,51"><scu uid="20" label="Investigators investigating Doolittle" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Senator Byron Dorgan, a North Dakota Democrat who, like Burns, sits on a congressional committee that oversees Indian tribes' issues, returned $67,000 in Abramoff-related donations a few days before Burns and Baucus gave back their campaign cash.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Almost from the start, Abramoff struck some rival lobbyists as a strange figure who operated on the margins.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Although we are an arm of the RNC, we must become financially self-sufficient.&quot;</line><line>He set up at least two tax-exempt groups to raise money - over the objections of an RNC lawyer who warned that such groups could not legally engage in political activities.</line><line>Memos indicate that three months earlier, in the summer of 1982, bills were going unpaid.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Mysterious Entrance</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>While Abramoff's cooperation is a major boon to prosecutors, his admissions of fraud this week also could provide ammunition against him if he testifies against lawmakers, some ethics lawyers said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Jack was a freebooting pirate as far as I was concerned,&quot; said a Washington attorney, Mark Braden, then the RNC's house counsel.</line><line>Greener scribbled on an Abramoff memo that described efforts to &quot;smash&quot; PIRGs and Uni d States Student Association chapters, and &quot;drive the final nail into their coffin sometime within the next year.&quot;</line><line>The first was its &quot;Poland Will Be Free&quot; campaign to support the democracy movement then under siege by the Polish communist government.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>DeLay, a Christian conservative, did not quite know what to make of Abramoff, who wore a beard and a yarmulke.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>His agreement to plead guilty to three criminal counts and cooperate with prosecutors threatens to ensnare other lawmakers or their aides -- Republicans and possibly some Democrats.</line><line>As for the perception of lobbying as a profession, &quot;It's confirmed everybody's worst fears about lobbyists -- that they double-deal, that they're not aboveboard,&quot; Jonas said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>So were loans to the College Republicans, but a July 1982 memo from Abramoff to his father, Frank, shows that he borrowed $5,000 for the group.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>The plea agreement could spare Abramoff the maximum sentence of 30 years in prison, but that depends on whether he provides valuable assistance in the corruption investigation, which is believed to focus on as many as 20 people, either members of Congress or top congressional aides.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Capitol Hill sources have also suggested that Abramoff gave free meals and drinks at his restaurant to lawmakers, in violation of a congressional rule barring gifts worth more than $50.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;We thought the meeting had gone well, that they listened to our concerns and were going to look into some things,&quot; Gamar-Heinlein said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Abramoff and his crew busted the College Republicans' budget with a 1982 national direct-mail fundraising campaign that ended up &quot;a colossal flop,&quot; said Bond, then deputy director of the party's national committee.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="3,35,43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Questions about Abramoff's financial management prompted rumors to circulate within the organization.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>&quot;I hope I can merit forgiveness from the Almighty and those I've wronged or caused to suffer.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Champing at the RNC bit<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Abramoff also counted on his father, who had a wealth of connections from his days as president of the Diners Club credit card company.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>I don't remember what precipitated it, but I remember [the incident].</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>At Reagan's 72nd-birthday party at the White House, Reed introduced Abramoff to his future wife, Pam Alexander, who was working with Reed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>One competitor in Abramoff's 1983 race for reelection accused Abramoff not only of generating a debt but of embezzling money that he had deposited into a Swiss bank account.</line><line>&quot;It was open warfare in the halls of the RNC between the Reaganites and the Bushyites,&quot; said Erickson.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>That could shift public attitudes sharply against the GOP.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>&quot;We weren't outside the box,&quot; the former Preston Gates colleague said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>By the early 1980s, direct mail had become a popular fund-raising tool for political groups, particularly on the right.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>&quot;In Espy, they didn't have the equivalent of an Abramoff or Scanlon connecting the dots,&quot; Gross said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Bad use of words!&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>If he lives up to the terms of his plea agreement, he is expected to face about 10 years in prison.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>The playacting provided a clue to how Abramoff saw himself -- the power behind the scenes who directed millions of dollars in Indian gambling proceeds to favored lawmakers, the puppet master who pulled the strings of officials in key places, the businessman who was building an international casino empire.</line><line>&quot;Jack was cutting deals all over town.</line><line>Afterward, Lehrman fired Abramoff amid a dispute about the handling of the group's $3 million budget.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Abramoff distributed on campuses 900 copies of a book called &quot;Target America,&quot; which posited that the Soviets had planted 4,000 journalist-agents in the American media to pursue a &quot;massive secret propaganda campaign,&quot; according to memos.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>House Democratic leader Nancy Pelosi said Abramoff's confession in court was &quot;not a surprise because this Republican Congress is the most corrupt in history and the American people are paying the price.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Justice Department prosecutors are pressing him and his lawyers to settle fraud and bribery allegations by the end of this week, sources knowledgeable about the case said.</line><line>For a time, all things seemed possible.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>But while DeLay limited his handouts to fellow Republicans, Abramoff spread his money around to lawmakers and candidates in both parties.</line><line>&quot;What it does is shine a very bright light on our campaign finance system,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Researcher Alice Crites contributed to this report.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Abramoff, now 47, had mammoth ambitions.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Young conservatives were enthralled, after years of feeling alienated on liberal college campuses.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>Griles, whose memory was fuzzy on just about everything, told the committee that he met with Auburn casino critics because of an inquiry from a congressman, although he didn't name Doolittle.</line><line>In both the Jena and United Auburn matters, the Interior Department was being asked to take non-Indian land into trust -- essentially accepting title to lands on the tribes' behalf -- so that they would qualify for a casino under an exception to the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Our job,&quot; Abramoff wrote, &quot;is to remove liberals &quot;from power permanently - [from] student newspaper and radio stations, student governments, and academia.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="0,9"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>&quot;My sense of this is that voters are cynical and angry to start, and that more scandal just makes matters worse,&quot; said Peter Fenn, a veteran Democratic consultant and former congressional staffer.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>John Jonas, a lobbyist at Patton Boggs, said he expects &quot;less partying, less gifting, more awareness about compliance&quot; with rules that have been &quot;observed in the breach.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Their boss had become increasingly frenzied about money and flouted the rules.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>In the summer of 1981, Abramoff, Norquist, and Reed joined thousands of young conservatives flocking to the nation's capital, following a 70-year-old former movie actor who offered sustenance for their patriotic hunger.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>WASHINGTON - Former high-powered lobbyist Jack Abramoff, a longtime associate of top Republican leaders, pleaded guilty Tuesday to conspiracy, fraud and tax evasion and agreed to cooperate with federal officials investigating political corruption in the nation's capital.<annotation scu-count="9" sum-count="7" sums="11,14,23,25,29,44,51"><scu uid="8" label="Abramoff agreed to cooperate" weight="4"/><scu uid="8" label="Abramoff agreed to cooperate" weight="4"/><scu uid="34" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to conspiracy" weight="3"/><scu uid="34" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to conspiracy" weight="3"/><scu uid="35" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to fraud" weight="1"/><scu uid="35" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to fraud" weight="1"/><scu uid="36" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to tax evasion" weight="1"/><scu uid="36" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to tax evasion" weight="1"/><scu uid="36" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to tax evasion" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>President George W. Bush's re-election campaign is returning thousands of dollars in campaign contributions connected to Jack Abramoff, the Republican lobbyist who has admitted to bribing lawmakers in a case that is leading to a widespread corruption probe involving top Washington officials.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="8" sums="11,19,25,33,43,48,49,5"><scu uid="28" label="President Bush returning campaign money" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Federal investigators are now looking into whether Griles interceded on behalf of Abramoff and improperly discussed a job with the lobbyist while in a position to affect his clients.</line><line>He even turned up as a representative of the Pakistani military when Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto went to Washington in 1995 to seek the return of $600 million the Islamabad government had paid for 28 F-16 fighters.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>But in the eyes of the College Republicans, the Polish regime wasn't the only Moscow puppet - so, too, were liberal student groups, the American media, leftist professors, and nuclear-freeze activists.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>In addition to the corruption investigation in Washington, Abramoff had been facing trial on fraud charges this month in Miami in connection with the purchase of a Florida casino cruise ship company.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>more</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;He had a strong belief in his own correctness.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Actors in the film said they saw South African soldiers on the set.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>&quot;Members of Congress try to hold onto as much money as possible, until it becomes politically distasteful to hold onto it,&quot; said David Donnelly, national campaigns director for the Public Campaign Action Fund.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>R. Alexander Acosta, the acting U.S. attorney in Miami, said the Florida investigation is continuing, led by Assistant U.S. Attorney Lawrence LaVecchio.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>The statement, the court papers say, was calculated to pressure the owner of SunCruz to sell on terms favorable to Abramoff.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>If a lawmaker is not personally tied to any possible illegal activity involving Abramoff, then giving the money back could burnish his or her image with voters, Malbin said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He says nothing,&quot; recalled one of the lobbyists.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line><line>They were joined by Ralph Reed, an ambitious Georgian whose later Christian conversion would fuel his rise to national political prominence.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Although he organized it as a nonpartisan, tax-exempt group, Abramoff served as chairman of both the foundation and the College Republicans.</line><line>It was damn the torpedoes, full speed ahead.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Bradley has returned such campaign contributions; Bass hasn't, but has called for DeLay to be replaced as the House leader.</line><line>The Abramoff and DeLay cases, Democrats believe, could help them pick up some seats next year and perhaps even regain majority control of the House.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;This is really a tragedy in the literal sense,&quot; said James Higgins, who succeeded Abramoff as College Republicans chairman.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>Other e-mails revealed that Abramoff and his associates were lobbying Griles hard at the Interior Department, and in 2003 had even offered him a job, though Griles testified that he doesn't remember it that way.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="16"><scu uid="21" label="Investigators investigating Griles" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>As the party in power, Republicans know they stand to lose more if voters take retribution in November.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Things happened because Jack willed them to happen.&quot;</line><line>&quot;With $250,000 it is impossible for us to run even a skeletal field effort,&quot; Abramoff complained in a memorandum.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>&quot;In a case of nuance, when you don't have eyewitnesses who are participants in a transaction, you have a problem,&quot; Brand said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>Abramoff's travels with his longtime friend, former House Majority Leader Tom DeLay, R-Texas, were already under investigation before Tuesday's plea agreement.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="25,37,6"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>But those working on behalf of the United Auburn tribe said Doolittle did not fully flex his political muscle with the Bush administration to try to kill the casino -- another sign that Doolittle was not necessarily advancing Abramoff's interests.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He folded his arms and refused.</line><line>When his crack administrative assistant Susan Ralston bolted for a position with White House political adviser Karl Rove, Abramoff told colleagues he had gotten her the job even though it was Ralston's old boss, Reed, who made it happen, her former colleagues said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>The College Republican tactics and unpaid bills led the RNC to demand that Abramoff leave the building and move the group elsewhere, former RNC officials said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>WASHINGTON - Members of Congress who once counted on super-lobbyist Jack Abramoff to help finance their campaigns have begun returning the cash they got from him and his clients, signaling a growing worry that ethics - and the scandal surrounding Abramoff - will become issues that could affect close House and Senate races in next year's midterm elections.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="49"><scu uid="26" label="Lawmakers returning campaign money" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>While the e-mails reveal that Abramoff saw a precedent for the Coushattas if the Auburn deal was rejected, Dickstein said the fact that Doolittle was not at the January meeting signaled that the congressman was not going to battle the Interior Department over it.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Many legislators under investigation, such as Rep. Robert W. Ney, R-Ohio, have denied any wrongdoing and have said that, like the tribes, they were defrauded by Abramoff.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>For a period of time now, members of Congress will be concerned about even legitimate contact with the lobbying world.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Unless he reaches a plea deal, he faces trial Jan. 9 in Florida in a related fraud case.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>Abramoff's cooperation has made lawmakers nervous.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>&quot;If we go down the road of assessing what's in the mind and hearts of every donor, we might find ourselves in tricky waters,&quot; said Diana Aviv, president and chief executive of Independent Sector, a nonprofit group that represents more than 600 American charities.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He sought to build the biggest lobbying portfolio in town.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Neither Norquist nor Reed has been charged with wrongdoing.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>Doolittle spokeswoman Laura Blackann said the congressman arranged meetings between the Interior Department and local government officials but said he did not attend.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>He predicted that lawmakers who accepted contributions from Abramoff may face serious questions from their constituents on the campaign trail.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>McClellan said Bush does not know Abramoff, although it's possible that the two met at three holiday receptions Abramoff attended at the White House, McClellan said.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>You can see his early prevarication.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Jack Abramoff liked to slip into dialogue from &quot;The Godfather&quot; as he led his lobbying colleagues in planning their next conquest on Capitol Hill.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="7" sums="12,23,36,38,42,44,8"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>His detractors at the RNC took a different view.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Attorneys, however, noted that there are key differences in the Abramoff case.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Their ideas will serve as the starting point for what is expected to be a vigorous debate.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Abramoff was in frequent contact with Marine Lt. Col. Oliver L. North, the Reagan White House's Iran-Contra mastermind, about grass-roots efforts to lobby Congress for the Nicaraguan Contras, according to records in the National Security Archive.</line><line>He was a generous patron in his Orthodox Jewish community, starting a boys' religious school in Maryland.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Erickson, then a student who was elected College Republican treasurer under Abramoff in 1983, disputed this version of events, saying the RNC was reclaiming prime office space from the College Republicans and other affiliates.</line><line>&quot;Such organizations may not engage directly or indirectly in political activities,&quot; Braden wrote.</line><line>Like other RNC affiliates - groups that represent GOP women, African-Americans, and the like - the College Republicans were allocated an annual budget.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>As for the charities, they are happy to get the Abramoff money, if a teensy bit uncomfortable with the attendant publicity.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>The Justice Department will pursue the investigation &quot;wherever it goes,&quot; Assistant Attorney General Alice Fisher told reporters at a news conference after Abramoff's court appearance.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="29,43"><scu uid="14" label="Abramoff's schemes investigated by Justice Dept" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Some political strategists and congressmen believe it's not necessary to return campaign donations simply because the contributor is under investigation.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>She doesn't recall whether Griles attended.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>They could, and did, take credit for helping orchestrate Reagan's victory in Massachusetts - a state so liberal it stood alone in George McGovern's 1972 column.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>With an eye on November's elections, Republicans have sought to limit the damage to themselves by portraying the scandal as bipartisan, describing Abramoff as an equal-opportunity dispenser of campaign cash and largesse.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>With Norquist's help, Abramoff secured a spot on the transition team for the Interior Department after George W. Bush's election as president in 2000.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>By then, his four-year tenure had made him a divisive figure.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>A November Washington Post-ABC News poll asked Americans whether they thought Democrats or Republicans were better on ethical matters; 16 percent said Democrats, 12 percent said Republicans and 71 percent said there was not much difference between the two parties.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;You could never get a straight answer,&quot; he said.</line><line>Norquist and Reed did not return telephone calls.</line><line>Looking back, Abramoff's critics inside the Republican Party say his tenure at the College Republicans should have provided a crystal ball into the turns his life might take.</line><line>Ronald Kaufman, then the RNC's political director, described Abramoff's management as &quot;living on the edge....</line><line>But they brought to their cause the same question-authority irreverence that had been the hallmark of leftist baby boomers.</line><line>But it was also costly, and would lead to the demise of a number of New Right groups.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Prosecutors are now expected to turn their attention to congressional aides and former Capitol Hill staffers who went to work for Abramoff in order to learn more about the actions of members of Congress.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>DeLay voted against his party on the Internet anti-gambling legislation which was designed to make it easier for authorities to stop online gambling sites.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Unbeknownst to the RNC, he launched an expensive direct-mail campaign that left the group in debt, and vendors complaining about unpaid bills.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>Give it back to Jack Abramoff?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Abramoff explained that he was &quot;close to Newt.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>Abramoff also is a longtime associate of other top GOP figures, including Americans for Tax Reform founder Grover Norquist and former Christian Coalition chief Ralph Reed, now a candidate for lieutenant governor in Georgia.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>This inside account of Abramoff's career is drawn from interviews with government officials and former associates in the lobbying shops of Preston Gates &amp; Ellis LLP and Greenberg Traurig LLP; thousands of court and government records; and hundreds of e-mails obtained by The Washington Post, as well as those released by Senate investigators.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>Abramoff and his former partner, Adam Kidan, are charged with concocting a false $23 million (euro19 million) wire transfer making it appear they contributed a sizable stake of their own cash into the $147.5 million (euro122.1 million) purchase of cruise ships.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;We thought it was a sign that he was not going to go to the mat over this.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Some former lawmakers said even bigger changes may be needed to restore public confidence in how Washington works.</line><line>&quot;That hurts the legitimate practice of the profession.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>But on Capitol Hill, lawmakers are uneasy, worried that any connection to Abramoff could become a campaign liability that far outweighs the campaign help he may have given them.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>One of Abramoff's most audacious adventures involved Jonas Savimbi, the Angolan rebel leader who had U.S. support but was later found to have ordered the murders of his movement's representative to the United States and that man's relatives.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>But the fallout from the Abramoff scandal has hurt their reputations, and ethical questions now cloud Reed's race for Georgia's lieutenant governor.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>According to an analysis prepared by the nonpartisan Center for Responsive Politics, Abramoff and his clients doled out more than $4.4 million to candidates since 2000, with $1.5 million of the money going to Democrats.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>Abramoff pleaded guilty Tuesday to conspiracy, mail fraud and tax evasion, with his conduct outlined in court papers that refers to &quot;a stream of things of value to public officials in exchange for a series of official acts and influence.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He introduced his son around, and the Marianas became one of the first important clients of the new lobbyist.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>Abramoff, whom Doolittle described as a close friend, had a tribal client thousands of miles away in Louisiana that could have benefited from the precedent if Doolittle and other critics succeeded in persuading the U.S. Department of Interior to stop Thunder Valley in 2002.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="10"/></line><line>-- Italia Federici, head of the Council of Republicans for Environmental Advocacy, which was receiving large contributions from Abramoff clients at the time, sent a message to Interior Secretary Gale Norton's communications director in February 2001 that Doolittle was working with Christian Coalition Director Ralph Reed &quot;on the California and Louisiana situations.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Now Abramoff has become a symbol of a system out of control.</line><line>Now, some GOP strategists fear that the fallout from his case could affect the party's efforts to keep control in the November mid-term elections.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>In return for such assistance, federal prosecutors will recommend a sentence of 9 1/2 to 11 years.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>It was painful.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>But if, as many political analysts suspect, some senators or House members are linked to Abramoff and potentially illegal activity, Malbin said, then &quot;returning the check won't begin to take care of the problem.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Bond and Kaufman were fiercely loyal to Bush and loathed Ronald Reagan.&quot;</line><line>&quot;We fought, begged, and pleaded&quot; for more funding, recalled Erickson.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>&quot;We were outside the universe.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>The new team, allies recalled, berated Republican moderates as &quot;Bushyites&quot; - a reference to the vice president - and &quot;squishes&quot; who were too eager to cut deals with Democrats on Capitol Hill, or with the Russians at superpower summits.</line><line>An Abramoff spokesman, Andrew Blum, issued a &quot;no comment&quot; in response to questions for this article.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Among the deals being scrutinized are contributions from the tribes who hired Abramoff to politicians and political groups associated with him, and overseas trips paid for by Abramoff and involving Tom DeLay, former House majority leader and Republican of Texas, among other political figures.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="22"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>During the last six years, Abramoff raised more than $5 million in campaign contributions, making him one of the most influential lobbyists in Washington, a city where, according to a Washington Post study last year, the number of registered lobbying firms now totals more than 2,000 and the amount of money officially spent by lobbyists exceeds $2 billion.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Norquist was one of the intellectual architects of the Republican Revolution and a muse for its leader, Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., soon to be speaker of the House.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;As such, the congressman was not personally involved in these meetings.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Those will be out.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Staffers lost their loyalty to members -- they were loyal to money.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>The appearance was made a day after Abramoff pleaded guilty in Washington to defrauding Indian tribal clients, conspiring to bribe members of Congress and evading taxes.<annotation scu-count="6" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="34" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to conspiracy" weight="3"/><scu uid="34" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to conspiracy" weight="3"/><scu uid="35" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to fraud" weight="1"/><scu uid="35" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to fraud" weight="1"/><scu uid="36" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to tax evasion" weight="1"/><scu uid="36" label="Abramoff pleaded guilty to tax evasion" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;Proving somebody accepted campaign contributions and expense-paid trips and then did something of benefit for Abramoff is not in and of itself proving bribery.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;I don't know the Auburn Rancheria,&quot; Griles testified.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Abramoff's team also cultivated Roger Stillwell, the Marianas desk officer at the Interior Department.</line><line>They organized Massachusetts college campuses in the 1980 election -- Abramoff while he was an undergraduate at Brandeis and Norquist at Harvard Business School -- to help Reagan pull an upset in the state.</line><line>Griles denied any wrongdoing in recent testimony to the Senate.</line><line>He had genuine inside connections but also puffed himself up with phony claims about his access.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Memos show that Abramoff set up the fund anyway.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line><line>Within the next couple of weeks, we must raise $50,000 in order to mail and phone bank these lists.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>The unfolding Abramoff affair &quot;has the potential to become the biggest congressional corruption scandal in modern times,&quot; said Fred Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, a non-profit organization that promotes campaign finance reforms.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>&quot;They're obviously worried,&quot; said Michael Malbin, director of the nonpartisan Campaign Finance Institute.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>They forged lifelong ties.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;What can we do?&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;We are replacing these leftists with committed conservatives.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>To make a bribery case against a legislator, prosecutors would need to prove that lawmakers knew Abramoff's gifts were in exchange for specific actions.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Baucus returned $18,892, including $1,892 he had failed to report for use of Abramoff's skybox at a Washington, D.C., sports arena.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>I think Abramoff is just part of a large pattern that has got to be rethought.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>They allege that Abramoff and Scanlon, once a top DeLay aide, who reached his own plea agreement with federal investigators last November, kept much of that money for themselves.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>Rudy did not return a phone call Tuesday at his lobbying firm.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line><line>White House press secretary Scott McClellan said Wednesday that Abramoff, his wife and the Indian tribal associates that he worked for, donated thousands to the Bush-Cheney 2004 campaign.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="41"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>That list is like the Holy Grail...</line><line>That lack of trust extended to finances.</line><line>The Reagan pilgrimage</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>&quot;The whole Abramoff matter is atypical,&quot; agreed Ed Rogers of Barbour Griffith &amp; Rogers.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>They moved to Washington, maneuvered to take over the College Republicans -- at the time a sleepy establishment organization -- and transformed it into a right-wing activist group.</line><line>Soon the younger Abramoff developed a key alliance with Rep. Tom DeLay, a conservative Republican from Texas who was working his way up in the House leadership.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="42"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Jack Abramoff represented the most flamboyant and extreme example of a brand of influence trading that flourished after the Republican takeover of the House of Representatives 11 years ago.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>However, at the White House, Bush spokesman Scott McClellan had a limited reaction to Abramoff's admissions of guilt.</line><line>His co-defendant in that case, Adam Kidan, agreed last month to testify against him.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Three men, including two associates of Kidan, have been charged in the killing.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>But neither Abramoff nor his 15-page plea agreement with the Justice Department identified any of those officials by name.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>But Gamar-Heinlein said the only help the Auburn casino critics got was from Doolittle, who helped arrange the meeting for the group but did not attend or send a representative.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>Prosecutors allege that Abramoff and his onetime partner, Michael Scanlon, overbilled their Indian tribe clients by millions of dollars and used that money to shower golf trips, sports and concert tickets, lavish dinners, skybox fund-raisers and campaign contributions on lawmakers, and the lawmakers in turn performed &quot;a series of official acts&quot; for Abramoff's clients.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>&quot;I'm sensing shadiness.</line><line>The aide recalled that Edwin A. Buckham, then DeLay's chief of staff, told his boss: &quot;We really need to work with Abramoff; he is going to be an important lobbyist and fundraiser.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>Republicans, who have controlled Capitol Hill since 1994, could be the hardest hit politically because Abramoff's links were the strongest and most numerous to members of the GOP.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>But Republicans worry about two possibilities.</line><line>Gingrich said Republican leaders in Congress should take the initiative to reform lobbying and campaign finance, rather than hoping to slip quietly past the current scandal.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>In Washington, the case is being run by Noel Hillman and Mary K. Butler of the public integrity section, and acting fraud section chief Paul E. Pelletier, along with prosecuting attorney Guy D. Singer.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>&quot;It is not a lesson of how business is done in Washington.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;The time is now,&quot; Reagan proclaimed, &quot;to recapture our destiny.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Florida prosecutors are working closely with attorneys from the Department of Justice's fraud and public integrity sections, who are overseeing a multiagency task force of 35 to 40 lawyers and investigators.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="9" label="Abramoff facing fraud charges in Florida" weight="2"/><scu uid="15" label="Abramoff's schemes investigated by Florida prosecutors" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>A year later, the College Republicans had accumulated &quot;rather large debt&quot; as Abramoff wrote in a November 1982 memo to a second direct-mail vendor.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Abramoff, a powerful Washington figure who owned a tony restaurant frequented by members of Congress, is under federal investigation for allegedly swindling American Indian tribes out of millions of dollars in lobbying fees and contributions to Abramoff's associates.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="13,22,55"><scu uid="16" label="Investigators investigating congressmen" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>The manual advised boycotting &quot;Marxist&quot; professors, and soliciting support from alumni college donors to oust them.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;Whenever I was asked by the congressional office at Interior to meet with certain members of Congress, I would do that.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Hints of Trouble</line><line>The Americans asked him to introduce himself.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>&quot;The standard that was set forth in the Espy case set a very high bar for quid pro quo and corrupt intent,&quot; Gross said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>But the society, along with many other charities large and small, is about to become a beneficiary of Abramoff's legendary largess.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>As part of the plea agreement, Abramoff is committed to making some $25 million in restitution to his victims and pay $1.2 million to the Internal Revenue Service for taxes he evaded.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Erickson defended Abramoff, saying he was promoting the cause of Reagan conservatism, not getting rich.</line><line>I am confident that an impartial study of the contrasts between the Carter/Mondale failure in Iran and the Reagan victory in Grenada will be most enlightening to voters 12 days before the general election.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>The astonished lobbyists for Bhutto learned that Abramoff had traveled to Islamabad and had sold his services to the Pakistani military without the prime minister's knowledge.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>The United Auburn matter came to a head midway through the 2001-2002 election cycle in which Abramoff and his tribal clients contributed about $30,000 to Doolittle's campaign committees and just months before the congressman's wife, Julie Doolittle, was hired in August 2002 to do fundraising and event planning for an Abramoff foundation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;You couldn't trust them not to get in trouble.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>The 1994 bill to which Rudy referred restored the Auburn Rancheria's tribal rights only after Doolittle had been assured the tribe wasn't going to get into gambling.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>It was the start of a career that would roil Washington 25 years later, and a phase of Abramoff's life that provided signposts toward his later demise.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="0,9"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>A 1997 Doolittle bill barring a casino near schools and churches and requiring agreements with local governments failed in the Senate, but became the basis for a negotiated deal between the tribe and Placer County on the location where the Thunder Valley casino was eventually built.</line><line>Blackann said Doolittle never coordinated with Reed and the Christian Coalition, as the Federici memo indicated.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Beyond that, however, is a fear that the scandal and that attention it could draw in the months before the election further sours the public on Washington and Congress.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Dear Sirs,&quot; Abramoff wrote to a printer.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>The legal standard for proving bribery is high because of a unanimous Supreme Court ruling in 1999 requiring prosecutors to show that gifts were given for specific government action.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Greener said: &quot;I have found in life that individuals who believe what they are doing is so right and so good and so important are also the individuals that have a high-frequency level of rationalizing away unacceptab</line><line>A short time after leaving the RNC building, Abramoff set up another nonprofit, the USA Foundation, soliciting money from such New Right donors as the Olin Foundation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>Yet the Abramoff plea bargain has been a boon to organizations as varied as the Boy Scouts and the Mississippi Hurricane Recovery Fund.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Stanley M. Brand, a former House counsel who was involved in the Sun-Diamond case, said that the Abramoff investigation appears to exceed the standard set by the Supreme Court.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>Michael Rosetti, who was legal counsel to Norton, testified at the committee that he smelled something fishy about the way the last-minute questions about the United Auburn casino were drawing Griles' attention, because Griles' duties at Interior did not include tribal gambling.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>As Abramoff saw it, the only hitch to his Napoleonic-scale ambition was the pea-sized budget that his sponsors at the Republican National Committee were willing to commit.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>The sale had been blocked by the U.S. government over concerns about Pakistan's nuclear program.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>So far the public has not identified corruption as solely a Republican problem.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051123.0159"><line>Because of his central role in much of Abramoff's business, Scanlon could be a key witness in any trials that arise from the case.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>&quot;Everybody lost their minds,&quot; recalled a former congressional staffer who lobbied with Abramoff at Preston Gates.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Memos from the period revealed Abramoff's intense focus on fund-raising and his readiness to use the connections of his Beverly Hills based-father, a Diners Club executive with connections to Reagan's kitchen cabinet.</line><line>But in a March 1982 memo, Braden, the RNC counsel, told Abramoff such a group would skirt tax laws.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>Abramoff has agreed to tell prosecutors and the FBI about alleged bribes to lawmakers and their aides on issues ranging from Internet gambling to wireless phone service in the House of Representatives.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>A quarter of a century ago, Abramoff and anti-tax crusader Grover Norquist were fellow Young Turks of the Reagan revolution.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>Ney denies wrongdoing, saying that &quot;at the time I dealt with Jack Abramoff, I obviously did not know, and had no way of knowing, the self-serving and fraudulent nature of Abramoff's activities.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="13,36,43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>Boulis died in a gangland-style hit a few months later.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>In recent weeks, Republican and Democratic lawmakers have sought to distance themselves from Abramoff, returning more than $200,000 in campaign contributions he had arranged while he was earning tens of millions of dollars as a lobbyist for American Indian tribes operating gambling casinos.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;I received last week a print order for stationery for the College Republican National Fund.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>At the same time, Abramoff dabbled as a Hollywood producer, shepherding an anticommunist movie, &quot;Red Scorpion,&quot; starring Dolph Lundgren, filmed in Namibia, which was then ruled by South Africa.</line><line>&quot;I have advised my client not to speak, except in court,&quot; said Neal Sonnett, one of his attorneys.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>&quot;There will be a push for increased oversight and disclosure of lobbying,&quot; said Douglas Pinkham, president of the Public Affairs Council, a lobbyist education group.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>The scandal, which has touched off a legislative scramble for reform, could also snare members of Congress.</line><line>Nina J. Easton is the author of the 2002 book &quot;Gang of Five.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>The meeting to which Rosetti and Griles appear to be referring occurred with Bureau of Indian Affairs officials in mid- to late January 2002, according to former Roseville Mayor Claudia Gamar-Heinlein, who attended it along with representatives from Rocklin and Lincoln.</line><line>Some at the Interior Department were suspicious that there was unusual attention being paid to the United Auburn request.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Carl Forti, spokesman for the National Republican Congressional Committee, said the committee has not recommend to GOP candidates that they return money from Abramoff or his clients.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., is giving $18,500 to a Christian mission in his home state.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell Feingold, D-Wis., who co-wrote campaign finance changes a few years ago, have introduced separate proposals that would crack down hard on lobbying as now practiced.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Frank Abramoff had once looked into operating a casino in the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands, U.S. territory that includes Saipan.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>&quot;They were just getting organized right at the time we were very far along in getting this approved,&quot; Dickstein said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He said he banished the three from GOP headquarters, telling Abramoff: &quot;You can't be trusted.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>&quot;Because of your generous donation we were able to fight Teddy Kennedy in Massachusetts.</line><line>After purging the moderates in the College Republican hierarchy, Abramoff and his team launched a series of events to build public support for Reagan's foreign policy.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>It's unclear whether the e-mails sparked the Justice Department's reported interest in Doolittle, R-Calif., as its corruption investigation digs deeper into Abramoff's connections on Capitol Hill.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Greener, an early Reagan supporter who says he was &quot;not a Bushie in any way, shape or form,&quot; also recalled that the disputes centered on the College Republicans' financial troubles and unanswered questions about where the money had gone.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060104.0675"><line>&quot;The corruption scheme with Mr. Abramoff is very extensive and we will continue to follow it wherever it leads,&quot; said Assistant Attorney General Alice Fisher, head of the Justice Department's criminal division.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>One of the key investigative strands that involves authorities in Florida and Washington is the investigation of Ney, chairman of the House Administration Committee.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060103.0140"><line>He also was a top fund-raiser for President Bush's re-election.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>Abramoff wallowed in his access, real and imagined.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="12"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060104.0143"><line>&quot;Still, I think it is a tough case.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20051226.0163"><line>Out of that they would ask me to meet with certain constituents.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Paul Erickson, who served as the College Republicans treasurer under Abramoff, dismissed the accusations of RNC officials as untrue and ideologically-based, saying Abramoff's critics were moderates allied with Vice President George H.W. Bush, who &quot;didn't want conservatism promoted in any sense.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>&quot;The Abramoff scandal is causing a re-examination of what lobbyists do in town,&quot; said R. Bruce Josten, executive vice president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He bought a fleet of casino boats.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060105.0223"><line>Sen. Hillary Rodham Clinton, D-N.Y., is giving $2,000 to New York charities that have not been publicly identified.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060206.0076"><line>Abramoff's team accused the United States Student Association - a 350-chapter liberal campus group that in 1982 protested Reagan's student aid cuts - of being a &quot;pro-Soviet, pro-terrorist, Marxist-Leninist organization.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>He tried to place several officials in Interior, including an unsuccessful attempt to land a former Marianas official in the top spot overseeing U.S. territories.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20060101.0116"><line>Burns, who has been targeted by Democrats in November's election, gave back $150,000 in contributions before Christmas, reversing an earlier position that he would not return the money.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20051228.0112"><line>&quot;Finally, he says, `I am Jack Abramoff,&quot;' recalled the lobbyist, a well-connected Democrat.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20060103.0070"><line>Abramoff was among the lobbyists most closely associated with the K Street Project, which was initiated by his friend, former House majority leader Tom DeLay, R-Texas, once 